[normal]Editorial Standards
[normal]&#xa0;[bold] [bold]Everything hinges on the
[normal] [bold]‘[bold]Editorial Guidelines[bold]’[bold] giving details of how the language used in the Guidelines can be interpreted
[normal] 
[normal]and how little understanding the ordinary licence fee 
[normal]payer 
[normal]has of the Guidelines which require a great deal of effort
[normal], both in time and intellectual ability,
[normal] to refer to.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The BBC 
[normal]say they 
[normal]set out to apologise quickly
[normal] when appropriate and respond
[normal] to the issues 
[normal]raised
[normal].
[normal]   
[normal]However, 
[normal]apologetic responses very oft
[normal]en leave the complainant frustrated and confused when the complaint is not upheld.
[normal]For example, letters in response to a complaint say things like “We would never deliberately set out to cause offence”*; “It is inevitable that programmes which are 
[normal]acceptable to some will occasionally strike others as distasteful and the only realistic and fair approach for us is to ensure that the range of our output is broad enough for everyone to feel that they are catered for at least some of the time”**; “We fee
[normal]l that our adult audience members should make up their own minds about what they personally find acceptable and we therefore try to ensure that enough detail is given about programmes for an informed decision to be made.”; “programmes containing strong lan
[normal]guage are usually signposted by presentation announcements so that no-one will be taken by surprise.”**
[normal]* ;
[normal] “There is no single set of standards in this area (
[normal]bad language on this occasion) 
[normal]on which the whole of society can agree.  The BBC has issued detail
[normal]ed guidelines to programme makers in order to try and minimise the risk of gratuitous offence.”****    (these BBC response comments come in one email dated 18 July 2011 Ref: CAS-869429-1H894G)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]* 
[normal]equally
[normal], this suggests that the BBC is sanguine if it has ca
[normal]used offence.
[normal]**this begs the question, where is the line on ‘broad range of output’ drawn and what percentage of the time should a licence fee payer expect to find something which doesn’t offend?  And why is it ‘fair’ to cater for the taste of the lowest 
[normal]common denominator?
[normal]*** this does not allow for channel hopping and accidentally coming across offensive material, even in programmes which sound innocuous enough.   This is a common complaint from our supporters.  
[normal]**** Surely there should be certain (eth
[normal]ical) standards for the BBC to abide by. The BBC’s “duty to use resources efficiently and proportionately in the interests of the licence fee payers as a whole” would be easier to achieve if the Editorial Guidelines were clear and specific, thus saving a g
[normal]reat deal of everyone’s time and energy and contributing to higher standards.    At present they are weighted in favour of editorial flexibility by being couched in permissive language.  This means that the complainant generally will receive a typical BBC 
[normal]brush
[normal] off.
[normal] 
[normal]It must be the responsibility of the Editor in Chief, the Director General, to ensure the Guidelines cannot be interpreted too widely by program
[normal]me makers and editorial staff, also, and of equal importance, to ensure that the Guidelines are easi
[normal]ly understood by the viewer and listener.
[normal]    For too long the Guidelines h
[normal]ave helped the BBC make a speciality
[normal] of
[normal] self-jus
[normal]tification which takes 
[normal]time and great determination to tackle
[normal] through the lengthy 
[normal]complaints procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is hardly surprising then,
[normal] that at a meeting with Fran O’Brien at the Trust three or four years ago  she told us they had only received one appeal on the subject of sexual content.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For a previous consultation, 
[normal]Director General, Mark Thompson,
[normal] 
[normal]said
[normal]:  [bold]“Your views help shape the 
[normal]decisions we take about the BBC’s services and the priorities we set the BBC’s management.”
[normal]    [bold]These words appear to
[normal] have been
[normal] empty rhetoric most of the time.    
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Guidelines are still lacking in clarity, ambiguous, open to interpretation and permissi
[normal]ve, as before, serving producers’ interests rather than the interests of the licence fee payer, and causing confusion among employees as to what is and is not allowed.  What is the resulta
[normal]nt 
[normal]cost of editorial and legal 
[normal]advice to programme makers?  If guide
[normal]lines were more specific and clear cut, there would be less need to resort to such advice – so is this costing the licence fee payer more money as some producers 
[normal]push boundaries
[normal] and editors make mistakes
[normal]?
